text.tspan: • Learn how to use layer blending modes for fun effects
• Become familiar with the paint bucket, gradient, & blur tools
• Combine layer blending modes and masking for digital face painting!
layer blending mode - one of the many ways you can blend two images together.
gradient - a fade from one color to another. Gradients can have multiple colors
that blend into one another (for example, the gradient below has eight.)
opacity - how transparet / see-through vs. how opaque an image is.
If a Hollywood makeup artist offered to do your look for Halloween, what face
paint, makeup, and/or hair dye would you ask for?
There are three main ways to use layer blending modes with an images. Nicki
is going to help us see what they are and how they look!

Blur your top layer by going to "Filters > Blur > Gaussian Blur" in the Gimp menu.
Use a blur radius of 20 and press 'OK'. Now, choose a 'Screen" blending mode for the
top layer. Adjust the opacity slider as desired.
Choose a 'Burn" blending mode for the top layer. Duplicate the top layer 2 times so
you have a total of 4 layers, the top 3 layers all in burn mode!
Invert the colors of your top layer by going to "Colors > Invert" in the Gimp menu.
Try the following layer blending modes for your top layer for differet 'alien' looks:
Color - this will make your skin a blue like the Avatar aliens.
Lighten Only - this will give your skin a bluish tint and whiten your hair
Darken Only - this will give your skin a 'radioactive' look!
